m the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]},{"name":"Greene","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Green  . In North America, this surname has assimilated cognates from other languages."],"variants":[{"name":"Green","meanings":["Transferred use of the Scottish surname, which originated in the Middle Ages from a contracted form of   Gregor .  It has become known as a girl's name in the English-speaking world through the fame of the actress  Greer Garson  (  1908–96 ), whose mother's maiden name it was."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Greene was born in 1131, in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England. She married Sir Abraham Cooke in 1154. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1170, in Essex, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1131–1170":"1131–1170","1129–